==Latin==
===Etymology===
# '''[[anno|annō]]''' is the [[ablative]] of '''[[annus]]''' (''[[year]])''
# '''[[Domini]]''' is the [[genitive]] of '''[[Dominus]]''' (''the [[Lord]]'')

===Expression===
'''annō Domini'''

# [[Latin]] for ''in the year of our Lord'' (often abbreviated [[AD|A.D.]] or [[AD]]). The religion-neutral [[CE]] (Common Era) is a non-Christian alternative.

====Usage====
*Usually placed after (or before) a year that succeeds the traditionally calculated birth of [[Jesus]].
*The [[w:Chicago Manual of Style|Chicago Manual of Style]] as well as most house styles require placing the [[A.D.]] before the date (e.g., AD 250), although in casual use it is frequently found following the date.

